<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-126-784  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 126 784.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 6 1990 v4 n5 p75(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple seeks to attract software developers to Far East. (BusinessBriefs)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (market share).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     ProgrammersSoftware DesignHardware VendorsMarket PenetrationBusiness PlanningAsia.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Apple's market share in the Far East. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Apple seeks to attract software developers to Far EastandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Apple is hoping to entice Mac software publishers intoFar East markets by offering information and assistance and by &quot;dispellingcopyright myths and misconceptions&quot; that have dissuaded developers.andM;&quot;The common perception when it comes to software is that [Far East countries]are a den of thieves and pirates.andP;  That's simply not true,&quot; said WilliamPeter Knight, Apple's senior counsel for Asia Pacific Operations, at acompany-sponsored seminar here last month.andM;Apple Far East, part of Asia Pacific Operations, is responsible for marketingin an area stretching from Pakistan to South Korea.andP;  It includes 15countries, dozens of major languages, and hundreds of minor languages anddialects.andM;Apple's revenues for the region grew by 60 percent in fiscal year 1989,according to Bill James, general manager of Apple Far East.andP;  Hong Kong,Taiwan, Korea and Singapore -- the so-called Four Tigers of newlyindustrialized Asia -- together accounted for 70 percent to 75 percent ofsales.andM;Apple officials said that software localization is the key to the company'sprospects in the region.andP;  Today, James said, Apple has a 7 percent marketshare in Taiwan and Korea, in terms of revenues; 12 percent in Singapore; and17 percent to 18 percent in Hong Kong.andM;&quot;We are willing to help [third parties] with information, and if we feel theproduct is a winner, then certainly [we will offer] Apple facilities andresources as well,&quot; James said.andP;  To assist developers considering the market,Apple is offering a 36-page document titled &quot;Myths andamp; Realities of Copyrightin the Asia Pacific Region.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>